poem:
The Kiridashi’s Glabersnatch  

Beware the kiridashi, child—its scritch-scritch-scritch on slate,  
It flicks a flenser-ink that peels the night to thinling scraps;  
Through scriberot, through linegash dark, it coils and cogitates,  
And every drip of drizz-script sticks like burrs in memory maps.  

He took a vorp-ruled scroll of tin, he honed a whispered quill,  
With clatterclack he counter-scored the parchment’s breathing back;  
He scrawled a sigil, splinter-sharp, to suture shadow’s will,  
Then whet his nerve upon the verse that keeps the black on black.  

Deep in the smudgegloom, pencils squeak like marmots freshly skinned;  
The kiridashi lifts its blade, a moon-thin glibberknife;  
It scrithes the silence, splits the hush, leaves stabbing strokes behind—  
Each punctuation puncture pumps the stanza into life.  

One flick!—the nib nails night to noon, a razor-runic thrust;  
The hero clenched his copper rule, cried “Snick—superscript—to me!”  
He slashed the stanza, split the scam, reduced the rush to dust;  
The line went limp, the ink unblinked, the darkness tore in three.  

Come galumphing home, young scribe, your ledger lightly bleeding;  
Let faulty fibers dangle where the margin used to be.  
Yet keep a nib-night handy—should the kiridashi, reading,  
Return to re-rewrite your right—beware beware, repeat.
